00:00:26.470 --> 00:00:28.910
Let’s get started.

00:00:28.910 --> 00:00:33.210
In this video, we’re going to take a look
at the Internet Protocol version 4, known

00:00:33.210 --> 00:00:36.100
as IPv4 header.

00:00:36.100 --> 00:00:41.930
This is used at Layer 3, to help send data
between devices on separate networks, even

00:00:41.930 --> 00:00:44.970
on other sides of the world over the Internet.

00:00:44.970 --> 00:00:46.550
This is known as routing.

00:00:46.550 --> 00:00:52.390
Originally, I planned this video to be a general
introduction to routing, but in the end I

00:00:52.390 --> 00:00:55.560
decided to split it up into separate parts.

00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:59.290
Let’s take a look at what we’ll cover
in this video.

00:00:59.290 --> 00:01:06.289
We’ll cover the IPv4 packet structure, or
more accurately, the IPv4 header which is

00:01:06.289 --> 00:01:10.200
used to encapsulate a TCP or UDP segment.

00:01:10.200 --> 00:01:14.680
Specifically, we will cover the fields of
the IPv4 header.

00:01:14.680 --> 00:01:19.110
We already looked in detail at two fields
of the header, the source and destination

00:01:19.110 --> 00:01:23.999
IP address fields, but there are quite a few
more fields to look at.

00:01:23.999 --> 00:01:26.179
And that’s all for this video!

00:01:26.179 --> 00:01:30.719
As I said, I originally planned to make this
a long, introduction to routing video.

00:01:30.719 --> 00:01:35.079
However, I don’t want to make these videos
too long, already the shortest videos are

00:01:35.079 --> 00:01:37.929
at least 30 minutes which is quite long I
think.

00:01:37.929 --> 00:01:42.499
So, I decided to split up routing into more
videos.

00:01:42.499 --> 00:01:46.679
This prevents the videos from getting too
long, but also lets me go more in depth on

00:01:46.679 --> 00:01:47.689
each topic.

00:01:47.689 --> 00:01:53.249
So, this video will focus exclusively on the
fields in the IPv4 header, and then future

00:01:53.249 --> 00:01:57.719
videos will will get more practical, with
hands-on configuration in the CLI.

00:01:57.719 --> 00:02:03.420
Since we’re going to look at the IPv4 header,
let’s review its position in a complete

00:02:03.420 --> 00:02:04.420
frame.

00:02:04.420 --> 00:02:10.810
So, the upper layers of the OSI model prepare
some data to be sent to another device.

00:02:10.810 --> 00:02:17.310
It is encapsulated in a layer 4 header, typically
using the TCP or UDP protocols, which we’ll

00:02:17.310 --> 00:02:19.900
talk about in a future lesson.

00:02:19.900 --> 00:02:24.410
This combination of data plus layer 4 header
is called a segment.

00:02:24.410 --> 00:02:30.340
The segment is encapsulated with a Layer 3
header, usually using the internet protocol,

00:02:30.340 --> 00:02:31.690
IP.

00:02:31.690 --> 00:02:37.000
This combination of data, layer 4 header,
and layer 3 header, is called a packet.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:43.080
Then, the layer 2 header and trailer are added,
and this is called a frame.

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:46.940
These units are called protocol data units,
or PDUs.

00:02:46.940 --> 00:02:53.490
For example, the layer 3 PDU is a packet,
and the layer 2 PDU is a frame.

00:02:53.490 --> 00:02:58.100
For this lesson, we’ll focus on this Layer
3 header, as it contains the information that

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:01.730
is needed to route this packet to its destination.

00:03:01.730 --> 00:03:07.390
Note that, since we’ll be focusing on Layer
3 here, I’ll usually be using the term ‘packet’,

00:03:07.390 --> 00:03:10.700
talking about ‘routing packets’, rather than frames.

00:03:10.700 --> 00:03:16.720
So, thanks to Wikipedia for this chart of
the IPv4 header structure.

00:03:16.720 --> 00:03:20.710
As you can see, it’s a bit more complicated
than the Ethernet header.

00:03:20.710 --> 00:03:24.750
To be honest, I doubt that it will be necessary
for you to memorize the exact structure of

00:03:24.750 --> 00:03:29.300
the header, the
size of each field, etc, for the CCNA test,

00:03:29.300 --> 00:03:32.680
but I can’t make any guarantees, I didn’t
make the test.

00:03:32.680 --> 00:03:37.150
What I recommend is just getting to know the purpose
of each field of the header, which we’ll

00:03:37.150 --> 00:03:39.010
cover now.

00:03:39.010 --> 00:03:43.041
By the way, if you’re wondering how to read
this chart, it’s read left to right, top

00:03:43.041 --> 00:03:49.690
to bottom, so this is the first bit of the
header, and this is the last bit of the header.

00:03:49.690 --> 00:03:54.130
So, let’s quickly go through each field
of the header so you’re familiar with its

00:03:54.130 --> 00:03:56.380
purpose.

00:03:56.380 --> 00:03:58.910
First up is the ‘Version’ field of the
header.

00:03:58.910 --> 00:04:02.760
It’s length is 4 bits, half of one octet.

00:04:02.760 --> 00:04:05.480
It’s purpose is straight forward.

00:04:05.480 --> 00:04:08.400
It identifies the version of IP used.

00:04:08.400 --> 00:04:14.670
Now, there are only two versions of IP in
use, IPv4, which is simply identified with

00:04:14.670 --> 00:04:20.249
a value of 4 in this field, or 0 1 0 0 in
binary.

00:04:20.249 --> 00:04:29.059
The other version is Ipv6, which is identified
with a value of 6, or 0 1 1 0 in binary.

00:04:29.059 --> 00:04:31.389
Now you may wonder what happened to IPv5?

00:04:31.389 --> 00:04:38.490
Well there was an experimental protocol called
Internet Stream Protocol which uses an Internet

00:04:38.490 --> 00:04:42.689
Protocol value of 5, but it was never publically
used.

00:04:42.689 --> 00:04:45.490
So, you could say that’s the lost IPv5.

00:04:45.490 --> 00:04:50.900
Now, we’re focusing on the IPv4 header,
so this field of the header will always have

00:04:50.900 --> 00:04:53.159
a value of 4.

00:04:53.159 --> 00:04:58.400
The IPv6 header has a different structure
than the IPv4 header, so if the value of this

00:04:58.400 --> 00:05:03.939
field is 6 the rest of the header will have
a different structure.

00:05:03.939 --> 00:05:08.090
Next up is the Internet Header Length, or
IHL, field.

00:05:08.090 --> 00:05:12.550
It’s also 4 bits in length, half of one
octet.

00:05:12.550 --> 00:05:19.289
The final field of the IPv4 header (Options)
is variable in length, so this field is necessary

00:05:19.289 --> 00:05:21.460
to indicate the total length of the header.

00:05:21.460 --> 00:05:27.949
Here’s an important part to remember: This
field specifies the length of the header IN

00:05:27.949 --> 00:05:29.919
4-BYTE INCREMENTS.

00:05:29.919 --> 00:05:36.629
For example, if the value in this field is
5, 5 times 4-bytes is 20, so that means that

00:05:36.629 --> 00:05:40.580
length of the header is 20 bytes.

00:05:40.580 --> 00:05:46.310
The minimum value in this field is 5, which
as I just said is equal to 20 bytes.

00:05:46.310 --> 00:05:52.639
That’s the length of the IP packet WITHOUT
any IP options at the end, so an empty options

00:05:52.639 --> 00:05:54.259
field.

00:05:54.259 --> 00:06:00.559
The maximum value is 15, which is the maximum
value of 4 bits, As you can see here, the

00:06:00.559 --> 00:06:06.389
values of the 4 bits are 1, 2, 4, and 8, adding
them up results in 15.

00:06:06.389 --> 00:06:11.740
So, 15 x 4 bytes is equal to 60 bytes.

00:06:11.740 --> 00:06:16.240
That means the maximum length of the IP options
field is 40 bytes.

00:06:16.240 --> 00:06:23.009
So, an IPv4 header with no options field is
20 bytes in length, and that’s the minimum length

00:06:23.009 --> 00:06:24.639
of an IPv4 header.

00:06:24.639 --> 00:06:31.919
And, an IPv4 with a maximum length options
field, 40 bytes, has a length of 60 bytes,

00:06:31.919 --> 00:06:35.080
and that’s the maximum length of an IPv4 header.

00:06:35.080 --> 00:06:40.550
Okay, that’s the IHL field of the IPv4 header.

00:06:40.550 --> 00:06:42.930
Next is the DSCP field.

00:06:42.930 --> 00:06:51.749
DSCP stand for differentiated services code
point, and the field’s length is 6 bits.

00:06:51.749 --> 00:06:55.779
This field is used for QoS, quality of service.

00:06:55.779 --> 00:07:02.650
Basic QoS is a topic on the CCNA so I will
make a dedicated video about it later.

00:07:02.650 --> 00:07:10.379
Essentially, it is used to prioritize delay-sensitive
data, such as streaming voice and video.

00:07:10.379 --> 00:07:15.020
If you’re loading a web page and the Internet
is a little slow, it’s not a big deal.

00:07:15.020 --> 00:07:19.770
However, if you’re having a skype call and
there’s terrible delay, or the audio and

00:07:19.770 --> 00:07:24.080
video keep freezing, it can totally ruin the
experience.

00:07:24.080 --> 00:07:30.050
This field is used to identify which traffic
should receive priority treatment.

00:07:30.050 --> 00:07:36.030
Next up is the ECN field, which stands for
explicit congestion notification and has a

00:07:36.030 --> 00:07:38.449
length of 2 bits.

00:07:38.449 --> 00:07:44.159
It provides end-to-end notification of network
congestion WITHOUT DROPPING PACKETS.

00:07:44.159 --> 00:07:49.930
Normally in a network, if the network is super
busy, if there is congestion, this is signalled

00:07:49.930 --> 00:07:52.119
by dropping packets.

00:07:52.119 --> 00:07:57.710
The ECN field provides a way to signal a congested
network without dropping packets.

00:07:57.710 --> 00:08:03.439
However, this is an optional field that requires
both endpoints, as well as the underlying

00:08:03.439 --> 00:08:07.680
network infrastructure, to support it.

00:08:07.680 --> 00:08:15.229
Next up is the Total Length field, and its
length is 16 bits, or 2 octets, 2 bytes.

00:08:15.229 --> 00:08:21.009
It indicates the total length of the packet,
including the IPv4 header and the encapsulated

00:08:21.009 --> 00:08:26.819
Layer 4 segment, which includes both the layer
4 header and the data.

00:08:26.819 --> 00:08:31.819
This is different than the IHL field, which
indicates only the length of the IPv4 header

00:08:31.819 --> 00:08:33.810
itself.

00:08:33.810 --> 00:08:40.140
This field indicates the length in bytes,
NOT IN 4-BYTE INCREMENTS LIKE THE IHL HEADER.

00:08:40.140 --> 00:08:46.060
So, a value of 20 in this field simply means
20 bytes.

00:08:46.060 --> 00:08:52.220
The minimum value in this field is 20, meaning
20 bytes, which is equal a minimum-sized IPv4

00:08:52.220 --> 00:08:55.680
header with no encapsulated data.

00:08:55.680 --> 00:09:03.710
The maximum value is 65,535, which is the
maximum value of 16 binary bits, all set to

00:09:03.710 --> 00:09:05.770
1.

00:09:05.770 --> 00:09:08.060
Let me just show you that calculation.

00:09:08.060 --> 00:09:13.910
Here are 16 bits, two octets, all set to 1.

00:09:13.910 --> 00:09:26.080
The first bit is equal to 1, then 2, then
4...8...16...32...64...128.

00:09:26.080 --> 00:09:31.300
This is as far as we went when looking at
a single octet in an IPv4 address.

00:09:31.300 --> 00:09:35.680
If you extend beyond 8 bits, the value keeps
doubling.

00:09:35.680 --> 00:09:54.740
Next is 256...512...1024...2048...4096...8192...16,384...and then
the 16th bit is 32,768.

00:09:54.740 --> 00:10:03.830
Add those all up, and you get 65535, the maximum
length of an IPv4 packet.

00:10:03.830 --> 00:10:09.310
Next up is the Identification field, which
is also 16 bits in length.

00:10:09.310 --> 00:10:14.930
If a packet is fragmented due to being too
large, this field is used to identify which

00:10:14.930 --> 00:10:20.210
packet the fragment belongs to, so it can
be reassembled again to make the original

00:10:20.210 --> 00:10:22.000
packet.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:27.510
All fragments of the same packet will have their
own IPv4 header with the same value in this

00:10:27.510 --> 00:10:31.150
field., so they can be reassembled later.

00:10:31.150 --> 00:10:36.490
Packets are fragmented if larger than the
MTU, which stands for Maximum Transmission

00:10:36.490 --> 00:10:38.710
Unit.

00:10:38.710 --> 00:10:43.240
The MTU is usually 1500 bytes.

00:10:43.240 --> 00:10:45.660
Remember the maximum size of an Ethernet frame?

00:10:45.660 --> 00:10:52.700
I mentioned that the maximum payload size
of an Ethernet frame is 1500 bytes, so these

00:10:52.700 --> 00:10:54.810
are related.

00:10:54.810 --> 00:11:01.170
And one last point, fragments are reassembled by
the receiving host.

00:11:01.170 --> 00:11:04.530
Next is the Flags field, which is 3 bits in
length.

00:11:04.530 --> 00:11:09.170
It is used to control and identify fragments.

00:11:09.170 --> 00:11:12.610
There are 3 bits, and they function like this.

00:11:12.610 --> 00:11:18.400
The first bit, bit 0, is reserved and always
set to 0.

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:22.620
Bit 1 is the don’t fragment bit, or DF bit.

00:11:22.620 --> 00:11:27.610
If it is set to 1, it means that the packet
should not be fragmented.

00:11:27.610 --> 00:11:31.360
Bit 2 is the more fragments, or MF bit.

00:11:31.360 --> 00:11:36.520
It is set to 1 if there are more fragments
in the packet, and then set to 0 for the last

00:11:36.520 --> 00:11:37.850
fragment.

00:11:37.850 --> 00:11:44.460
Also, if the packet is a whole, unfragmented
packet, the MF bit is set to 0, since there

00:11:44.460 --> 00:11:47.870
are no fragments.

00:11:47.870 --> 00:11:53.030
Next we have one more field related to packet
fragmentation, that is the fragment offset

00:11:53.030 --> 00:11:57.060
field, which is 13 bits in length.

00:11:57.060 --> 00:12:02.110
This field is used to indicate the position
of the fragment within the original, unfragmented

00:12:02.110 --> 00:12:04.180
IP packet.

00:12:04.180 --> 00:12:09.930
This allows fragmented packets to be reassembled
even if the fragments arrive out of order,

00:12:09.930 --> 00:12:15.420
since this field lets the receiver know the
original order of the fragments.

00:12:15.420 --> 00:12:20.040
Next up is the Time to Live Field, which is
8 bits in length.

00:12:20.040 --> 00:12:24.620
A router will drop a packet with a TTL of
0.

00:12:24.620 --> 00:12:28.950
So, this field is used to prevent infinite
loops.

00:12:28.950 --> 00:12:34.190
If a poor routing configuration causes a packet
to be continually sent around in a loop, never

00:12:34.190 --> 00:12:39.670
reaching its intended destination, if enough
traffic like that accumulates, it could causes

00:12:39.670 --> 00:12:43.540
network congestion, and eventually failure.

00:12:43.540 --> 00:12:48.800
This feature prevents that by happening, causing
looped traffic to be dropped when the TTL

00:12:48.800 --> 00:12:50.980
reaches 0.

00:12:50.980 --> 00:12:56.720
This field was originally designed to indicate
the packet’s maximum lifetime in seconds,

00:12:56.720 --> 00:13:01.310
in practice, however, this actually indicates
a ‘hop count’.

00:13:01.310 --> 00:13:06.340
Each time the packet arrives at a router on
the way to its destination, the router decreases

00:13:06.340 --> 00:13:12.860
the TTL by 1, until the packet reaches its
destination, or the TTL reaches 0 and the

00:13:12.860 --> 00:13:14.870
packet is dropped.

00:13:14.870 --> 00:13:19.480
The current recommended default TTL is 64.

00:13:19.480 --> 00:13:24.820
Next up is the Protocol field, which is also
8 bits in length.

00:13:24.820 --> 00:13:29.650
It indicates the protocol of the encapsulated
Layer 4 PDU.

00:13:29.650 --> 00:13:36.950
Typically, this will be one of the following:
TCP, which is indicated by a value of 6, or

00:13:36.950 --> 00:13:40.650
UDP, which is indicated by a value of 17.

00:13:40.650 --> 00:13:46.530
I haven’t talked about TCP and UDP yet,
but that I will make a dedicated video about

00:13:46.530 --> 00:13:48.290
them later.

00:13:48.290 --> 00:13:55.720
For now, try to remember their protocol numbers
of 6 for TCP and 17 for UDP.

00:13:55.720 --> 00:14:02.600
You might also see a value of 1, which is
used for ICMP, the protocol ping uses.

00:14:02.600 --> 00:14:09.860
Another one to remember is 89, which is OSPF,
which stands for Open Shortest Path First.

00:14:09.860 --> 00:14:15.700
OSPF is a dynamic routing protocol which allows
routers to learn routes to destinations from

00:14:15.700 --> 00:14:19.860
their neighbors, without us having to manually
configure the routes.

00:14:19.860 --> 00:14:26.390
We will cover OSPF in depth in this course,
so for now just try to remember the protocol number of

00:14:26.390 --> 00:14:27.390
89.

00:14:27.390 --> 00:14:33.120
If you’re curious, you can check a list
of protocol numbers at this page on wikipedia.

00:14:33.120 --> 00:14:38.760
Don’t worry about memorizing any others,
but try to remember these four.

00:14:38.760 --> 00:14:44.750
The included flashcards are extremely useful
for remembering little facts like these.

00:14:44.750 --> 00:14:49.930
Next is the header checksum field, which is
16 bits in length.

00:14:49.930 --> 00:14:56.540
It is a calculated checksum used to check
for errors in the Ipv4 header.

00:14:56.540 --> 00:15:01.320
When a router receives a packet, it calculates
the checksum of the header and compares it

00:15:01.320 --> 00:15:04.430
to the one in this field of the header.

00:15:04.430 --> 00:15:10.300
If the newly calculated checksum and the checksum
in the IPv4 header do not match, it means

00:15:10.300 --> 00:15:15.870
that an error has occurred in transmission,
so the router drops the packet.

00:15:15.870 --> 00:15:21.010
Note that this is only used to check for errors
in the IPv4 header, not in the encapsulated

00:15:21.010 --> 00:15:22.010
data.

00:15:22.010 --> 00:15:26.550
IP relies on the encapsulated protocol to
do that.

00:15:26.550 --> 00:15:33.070
Both UDP and TCP, the two Layer 4 protocols
most likely to be encapsulated, have checksum

00:15:33.070 --> 00:15:36.890
fields to check for errors in the encapsulated
data.

00:15:36.890 --> 00:15:43.110
Okay, next up are the Source and Destination
IP Address fields, which I covered in detail

00:15:43.110 --> 00:15:44.810
already.

00:15:44.810 --> 00:15:52.230
As you already know, they are 32 bits in length
each, as that is the length of an IPv4 address.

00:15:52.230 --> 00:15:58.890
The source IP address field indicates the
IPv4 address of the sender of the packet.

00:15:58.890 --> 00:16:04.240
The destination IP address field indicates
the IPv4 address of the intended receiver

00:16:04.240 --> 00:16:06.180
of the packet.

00:16:06.180 --> 00:16:14.190
Finally, the options field, which is optional
and can be 0 bits in length if not used, or

00:16:14.190 --> 00:16:18.920
up to 320 bits, 40 bytes, in length.

00:16:18.920 --> 00:16:24.860
This field is rarely used, however if the
IHL, Internet header length, field is greater

00:16:24.860 --> 00:16:29.260
than 5, is means that options are present.

00:16:29.260 --> 00:16:33.970
Here is a chart from Wikipedia showing the
structure of the Options field, you can check

00:16:33.970 --> 00:16:40.180
it out or read more online if you’re interested,
but for the purposes of CCNA studies I don’t

00:16:40.180 --> 00:16:42.710
think you need to worry about it.

00:16:42.710 --> 00:16:47.330
Okay, now we’ve covered all of the fields
of the IPv4 header.

00:16:47.330 --> 00:16:51.900
It’s a bit more complicated than the simple
Ethernet header and trailer we already learned

00:16:51.900 --> 00:16:56.820
about, but hopefully you understand the purpose
of each field now.

00:16:56.820 --> 00:17:02.581
For the purpose of the CCNA, I think the information
presented in this video is sufficient, but

00:17:02.581 --> 00:17:08.550
of course feel free to read more, a simple
Google search will give you many good resources.

00:17:08.550 --> 00:17:14.459
Also don’t forget to use the Anki flashcards
to help you remember everything.

00:17:14.459 --> 00:17:19.339
Now let’s go in depth and analyze a packet
capture from Wireshark.

00:17:19.339 --> 00:17:24.640
I showed you Wireshark before, and its an
extremely useful tool both for learning, and

00:17:24.640 --> 00:17:27.270
also in the real world to troubleshoot problems.

00:17:27.270 --> 00:17:33.070
This isn’t a wireshark course, but I will
show you wireshark at various points in this

00:17:33.070 --> 00:17:39.770
course, and if you have a lab with real Cisco
equipment, or a virtual lab using GNS3, I

00:17:39.770 --> 00:17:44.070
highly recommend you use Wireshark to examine
network traffic like this, it will really

00:17:44.070 --> 00:17:46.460
help you in your studies.

00:17:46.460 --> 00:17:51.610
But in either case, I will show you Wireshark
packet captures in this course, so don’t

00:17:51.610 --> 00:17:53.920
worry if you aren’t able to use it yourself.

00:17:53.920 --> 00:18:02.020
So, I sent a ping between two routers, notice
under the INFO column it says echo (ping)

00:18:02.020 --> 00:18:03.190
request.

00:18:03.190 --> 00:18:08.980
I have selected the frame here, meaning the
entire frame and you can see down here that

00:18:08.980 --> 00:18:11.500
the entire frame is highlighted.

00:18:11.500 --> 00:18:16.640
These digits are a hexadecimal representation
of the frame.

00:18:16.640 --> 00:18:21.490
Now I highlighted the Ethernet header, and
down at the bottom you can see only the Ethernet

00:18:21.490 --> 00:18:24.980
header section of the frame is highlighted.

00:18:24.980 --> 00:18:30.150
Then I highlight the IP header, and at the
bottom only the IP header section of the frame

00:18:30.150 --> 00:18:32.610
is highlighted.

00:18:32.610 --> 00:18:38.780
Then I highlight the packet’s payload, which
is Internet Control Message Protocol, or ICMP,

00:18:38.780 --> 00:18:44.310
the protocol used by ping, and you can see
the payload highlighted at the bottom.

00:18:44.310 --> 00:18:49.620
In this video we’re focusing on the IPv4
header, so let’s expand the Internet Protocol

00:18:49.620 --> 00:18:52.710
Version 4 information.

00:18:52.710 --> 00:18:59.160
Okay, so I’ve expanded the IPv4 header section
and zoomed up a bit, and here you can see

00:18:59.160 --> 00:19:03.880
all of the fields we looked at in this video,
except Options.

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:08.850
As I said, options are rarely used, and they
aren’t in this packet.

00:19:08.850 --> 00:19:15.490
First up, the Version field, and V you can see the
binary bits 0100 on the left, and it shows

00:19:15.490 --> 00:19:18.780
you that means version 4.

00:19:18.780 --> 00:19:22.340
Next is the header length which is the IHL
field.

00:19:22.340 --> 00:19:28.280
It has a binary value of 0101, which equals
5.

00:19:28.280 --> 00:19:34.740
Remember, this field indicates the length
in units of 4 bytes, so this value of 5 means

00:19:34.740 --> 00:19:37.980
a header length of 20 bytes.

00:19:37.980 --> 00:19:43.540
That is the minimum header length, and it
is the length of an IPv4 header with no options

00:19:43.540 --> 00:19:45.680
field.

00:19:45.680 --> 00:19:51.440
Next up is the differentiated services field,
and as you can see Wireshark categorizes both

00:19:51.440 --> 00:19:59.630
the DSCP, differentiated services codepoint,
and ECN, explicit congestion notification,

00:19:59.630 --> 00:20:02.600
fields under this section.

00:20:02.600 --> 00:20:06.920
Both are set to 0, as they are not being used.

00:20:06.920 --> 00:20:09.590
Next up is the total length.

00:20:09.590 --> 00:20:14.929
This represent the total length of the IP
packet in bytes, including both the header

00:20:14.929 --> 00:20:17.770
and the ICMP data it encapsulates.

00:20:17.770 --> 00:20:23.740
So, this 100 means that the total length is
100 bytes.

00:20:23.740 --> 00:20:26.730
Next is the identification field.

00:20:26.730 --> 00:20:29.760
This packet has an identification field of
5.

00:20:29.760 --> 00:20:36.210
It’s not fragmented, but if it were fragmented,
the other fragments belonging to this packet

00:20:36.210 --> 00:20:39.910
would also have a value of 5 here.

00:20:39.910 --> 00:20:42.790
Next up is the flags field.

00:20:42.790 --> 00:20:48.220
Notice that Wireshark also includes the fragment
offset field under this section.

00:20:48.220 --> 00:20:50.620
The reserved bit is always 0.

00:20:50.620 --> 00:20:53.970
That’s what ‘not set’ means by the way.

00:20:53.970 --> 00:21:00.450
I sometimes say ‘set to 0’ or ‘set to
1’, but another way of saying it is ‘not

00:21:00.450 --> 00:21:04.540
set’, which means 0, or ‘set’, which
means 1.

00:21:04.540 --> 00:21:12.420
The don’t fragment bit isn’t set, so this
packet can be fragmented, if necessary.

00:21:12.420 --> 00:21:18.550
The more fragments bit also isn’t set, which
is expected as the packet isn’t fragmented.

00:21:18.550 --> 00:21:24.280
The fragment offset field is also 0, which
is also expected in a packet that isn’t

00:21:24.280 --> 00:21:25.590
fragmented.

00:21:25.590 --> 00:21:30.800
Next is the Time to Live field, which is set
to 255, the maximum.

00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:39.150
Remember, the time to live field is 8 bits
in length, and 255 is the maximum 8-bit value.

00:21:39.150 --> 00:21:43.750
The protocol is ICMP, because I used ping.

00:21:43.750 --> 00:21:47.920
Notice the protocol value of 1 which indicates
this.

00:21:47.920 --> 00:21:50.980
You can see the header checksum here.

00:21:50.980 --> 00:21:54.320
Remember it’s a 16-bit value.

00:21:54.320 --> 00:22:01.800
0X indicates hexadecimal, and then each hexadecimal
digit is equal to 4 bits, so 4 times 4 is

00:22:01.800 --> 00:22:03.440
16, 16 bits.

00:22:03.440 --> 00:22:11.620
Here’s the source IP address, and finally
the destination IP address.

00:22:11.620 --> 00:22:16.980
The standard PING command on a Cisco router
will send 100-byte pings, which is why the

00:22:16.980 --> 00:22:19.420
ping I showed you wasn’t fragmented.

00:22:19.420 --> 00:22:29.590
But, I pinged once more, using this command
ping 192.168.1.2 SIZE 10000, which will send

00:22:29.590 --> 00:22:35.080
10,000 byte pings, much larger than the 1500
bytes MTU.

00:22:35.080 --> 00:22:39.100
So, this will cause fragmentation.

00:22:39.100 --> 00:22:43.350
As you can see here, there are a bunch of
IP fragments.

00:22:43.350 --> 00:22:47.000
They all say ‘reassembled in #13’.

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:48.580
What is #13?

00:22:48.580 --> 00:22:52.230
Well, it’s this ICMP echo request right here.

00:22:52.230 --> 00:22:58.180
Now, let’s take a look at some of the IPv4
header fields in these fragments.

00:22:58.180 --> 00:23:03.370
Okay, so these are the details of just the
first two fragments.

00:23:03.370 --> 00:23:10.060
First off, notice the total length of 1500
bytes, so this 10,000 byte ping was divided

00:23:10.060 --> 00:23:15.679
up into 1500 byte fragments, which is equal
to the MTU size.

00:23:15.679 --> 00:23:20.059
Then, notice the identification field of 1.

00:23:20.059 --> 00:23:24.120
This is different than the last packet I showed
you, but notice that the value is the same

00:23:24.120 --> 00:23:27.070
for these two fragments.

00:23:27.070 --> 00:23:30.030
Then take a look at the flags.

00:23:30.030 --> 00:23:34.850
Each of them has the more fragments bit set,
because neither of these is the last fragment in

00:23:34.850 --> 00:23:37.250
the packet.

00:23:37.250 --> 00:23:41.470
Also, notice that each of them has a different fragment
offset value, however, and that the first

00:23:41.470 --> 00:23:45.000
fragment has an offset of 0.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:50.580
Just one more thing, this time I sent a ping
and set the don’t fragment bit by adding

00:23:50.580 --> 00:23:53.840
the ‘df-bit’ option to the ping command.

00:23:53.840 --> 00:23:57.070
As you can see here, now the don’t fragment
bit is set.

00:23:57.070 --> 00:24:03.070
Because I didn’t set the size, the default
ping size of 100 bytes was used, so it was

00:24:03.070 --> 00:24:06.670
no problem that these packets weren’t allowed
to be fragmented.

00:24:06.670 --> 00:24:13.140
However, if I send pings that are larger than
the MTU, AND set the DF-bit, you can see the

00:24:13.140 --> 00:24:14.870
pings fail.

00:24:14.870 --> 00:24:21.920
They were too large to be sent unfragmented,
but also not allowed to be fragmented.

00:24:21.920 --> 00:24:26.390
Before moving on to today’s quiz let’s
review what we studied.

00:24:26.390 --> 00:24:32.720
We looked at the structure of an IPv4 packet,
more specifically the fields of the IPv4 header.

00:24:32.720 --> 00:24:34.260
That’s it.

00:24:34.260 --> 00:24:37.960
It doesn’t look like a lot when you list
it like this, but I’m sure you agree that

00:24:37.960 --> 00:24:40.300
was a lot of information.

00:24:40.300 --> 00:24:45.090
In the next video we’ll get more practical
and hands-on, getting into the CLI to see

00:24:45.090 --> 00:24:47.100
how to configure routes.

00:24:47.100 --> 00:24:51.260
Okay let’s move on to today’s quiz.

00:24:51.260 --> 00:24:55.890
In addition to the quiz, make sure to download
and use the Anki flashcards to help you remember

00:24:55.890 --> 00:24:58.520
all of the details you learned in this video.

00:24:58.520 --> 00:25:02.460
Let’s get started with question 1.

00:25:02.460 --> 00:25:08.440
What is the fixed binary value of the first
field of an IPv4 header?

00:25:08.440 --> 00:25:10.820
A, 0010.

00:25:10.820 --> 00:25:13.520
B, 0110.

00:25:13.520 --> 00:25:17.520
C, 0001.

00:25:17.520 --> 00:25:20.429
D, 0100.

00:25:20.429 --> 00:25:27.309
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:25:27.309 --> 00:25:31.250
The answer is D, 0100.

00:25:31.250 --> 00:25:35.429
The first field of the IPv4 header is the
version field.

00:25:35.429 --> 00:25:41.371
Because the question is about an IPv4, or
Internet Protocol VERSION 4 header, the version

00:25:41.371 --> 00:25:46.059
field is always set to 4, or 0100 in binary.

00:25:46.059 --> 00:25:49.990
let’s go to question 2.

00:25:49.990 --> 00:25:54.770
Which field will cause the packet to be dropped
if it has a value of 0?

00:25:54.770 --> 00:25:57.510
A, TTL.

00:25:57.510 --> 00:26:00.250
B, DSCP.

00:26:00.250 --> 00:26:02.990
C, IHL.

00:26:02.990 --> 00:26:05.730
D, ECN.

00:26:05.730 --> 00:26:12.260
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:26:12.260 --> 00:26:15.010
The answer is A, TTL.

00:26:15.010 --> 00:26:18.230
TTL stands for Time To Live.

00:26:18.230 --> 00:26:22.640
It is reduced by 1 at each router the packet
passes through.

00:26:22.640 --> 00:26:25.520
If it reaches 0, the packet is dropped.

00:26:25.520 --> 00:26:29.950
Let's go to question 3.

00:26:29.950 --> 00:26:34.570
How are errors in an IPv4 packet’s encapsulated
data detected?

00:26:34.570 --> 00:26:39.990
A, the IPv4 header checksum field checks for
errors.

00:26:39.990 --> 00:26:47.050
B, the encapsulated protocol, for example
TCP or UDP, checks for errors.

00:26:47.050 --> 00:26:52.220
C, Errors in the encapsulated data cannot
be detected.

00:26:52.220 --> 00:26:59.570
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:26:59.570 --> 00:27:04.710
The answer is B, the encapsulated protocol
checks for errors.

00:27:04.710 --> 00:27:10.440
The IPv4 Header Checksum field only checks
for errors in the IPv4 header itself.

00:27:10.440 --> 00:27:16.740
However, Layer 4 protocols like TCP or UDP
can use their checksum to check for errors

00:27:16.740 --> 00:27:18.530
in the encapsulated data.

00:27:18.530 --> 00:27:22.760
Let’s go to question 4.

00:27:22.760 --> 00:27:26.530
Which field of an Ipv4 header is variable
in length?

00:27:26.530 --> 00:27:28.950
A, options.

00:27:28.950 --> 00:27:31.620
B, header checksum.

00:27:31.620 --> 00:27:34.490
C, total length.

00:27:34.490 --> 00:27:37.429
D, IHL.

00:27:37.429 --> 00:27:44.020
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:27:44.020 --> 00:27:47.160
The answer is A, Options.

00:27:47.160 --> 00:27:52.320
The Options field can vary in length from
0 bits to 320 bits.

00:27:52.320 --> 00:27:55.669
The other fields are fixed-length.

00:27:55.669 --> 00:28:00.380
Although the Total Length and IHL fields are
used to represent the variable length of the

00:28:00.380 --> 00:28:05.429
IPv4 header and packet, the fields themselves
are fixed in length.

00:28:05.429 --> 00:28:10.140
Let’s go to question 5.

00:28:10.140 --> 00:28:16.840
Which bit will be set to 1 on all IPv4 packet
fragments except the last fragment?

00:28:16.840 --> 00:28:20.360
A, fragment offset bit.

00:28:20.360 --> 00:28:23.620
B, more fragments bit.

00:28:23.620 --> 00:28:26.770
C, dont fragment bit.

00:28:26.770 --> 00:28:30.410
D, packet fragment bit.

00:28:30.410 --> 00:28:37.429
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:28:37.429 --> 00:28:41.070
The answer is B, more fragments bits.

00:28:41.070 --> 00:28:47.040
The More Fragments bit, part of the Flags
field of the IPv4 header, is used to indicate

00:28:47.040 --> 00:28:52.010
that the current fragment is not the last
fragment of a fragmented packet.

00:28:52.010 --> 00:28:57.640
It is set to 1 on all fragments except the
last, which will set it to 0.

00:28:57.640 --> 00:29:03.000
A, fragment offset, is a 13-bit field in the
header, not a single bit.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:09.150
C, Don’t fragment bit, is used to prevent
a packet from being fragmented.

00:29:09.150 --> 00:29:14.850
And D, packet fragment bit, is not a real
bit in the IPv4 header.

00:29:14.850 --> 00:29:18.760
Okay, that’s all for the quiz.

